TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Effects of Negative Affectivity, Hierarchical Status, and Self-Determination on Workplace Victimization
AU  - Aquino, Karl
AU  - Grover, Steven L.
AU  - Bradfield, Murray
AU  - Allen, David G.
Y1  - 1999/06/01
PY  - 1999
DA  - 1999/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256918
DO  - 10.5465/256918
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 260
EP  - 272
VL  - 42
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study investigated the conditions under which employees are more or less likely to become targets of coworkers? aggressive actions. Results from a field survey showed people high in negative affectivity more often perceived themselves as victims, as did people who were low in the self-determination component of empowerment. In addition, hierarchical status appeared to buffer the influence of negative affectivity: Negative affectivity was not related to indirect victimization for higher-status people but was positively related to indirect victimization for lower-status people.
AB  - This study investigated the conditions under which employees are more or less likely to become targets of coworkers? aggressive actions. Results from a field survey showed people high in negative affectivity more often perceived themselves as victims, as did people who were low in the self-determination component of empowerment. In addition, hierarchical status appeared to buffer the influence of negative affectivity: Negative affectivity was not related to indirect victimization for higher-status people but was positively related to indirect victimization for lower-status people.
