TY  - JOUR
T1  - Examining the Actions of Organizations in Conflict: Evidence From the Delaware Court of Chancery
AU  - Conlon, Donald E.
AU  - Sullivan, Daniel P.
Y1  - 1999/06/01
PY  - 1999
DA  - 1999/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256922
DO  - 10.5465/256922
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 319
EP  - 329
VL  - 42
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We use the interpersonal dispute resolution literature to develop hypotheses regarding how organizations respond to adjudicated conflicts. Our hypotheses were tested with data from disputes litigated at the Court of Chancery of the State of Delaware, which has been called ?the chief arbiter of right and wrong in corporate America? New York Times, 1995). Our results underscore the important role that legal agents play in organization-level dispute resolution. We also highlight the different power bases of disputants as factors influencing favorable outcomes at the Chancery.
AB  - We use the interpersonal dispute resolution literature to develop hypotheses regarding how organizations respond to adjudicated conflicts. Our hypotheses were tested with data from disputes litigated at the Court of Chancery of the State of Delaware, which has been called ?the chief arbiter of right and wrong in corporate America? New York Times, 1995). Our results underscore the important role that legal agents play in organization-level dispute resolution. We also highlight the different power bases of disputants as factors influencing favorable outcomes at the Chancery.
